d gerygone also has a life span going up to almost three years. Taxonomy The Yellow-Bellied Gerygone was first named Gerygone Chrystogaster, in Greek khrusos means gold and gaster/gastros meaning belly. There are about 3 subspecies under Gerygone Chrysogaster, all three living in New Guinea that being, Notata, neglecta, and chrysogaster. George Robert Gray who was a part of the Zoological Society of London described and named the yellow-bellied gerygone in 1858. The gerygone chrysogaster neglecta was founded by Alfred Russel Wallace in 1865, thirteen years later in 1878 the gerygone chrysogaster Notata was named by Italian zoologist Tommaso Salvadori. Diet and foraging Yellow-Bellied Gerygone sing in small groups up to five birds and they forage together. These birds are insectivorous and have we no information about them being prey. As well as these birds being highly active, they are often found in mixed-species flocks, searching mostly on lower sections of trees for food. References", "shortSummary": "The yellow-bellied gerygone (Gerygone chrysogaster) is a species of bird in the family Acanthizidae. The Yellow-Bellied Gerygone is native…", "locations": ["新幾內亞島"], "lat": -6.0, "lng": 142.0, "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Gerygone_chrysogaster_-_themaskedlapwing_-_573192220.jpeg/960px-Gerygone_chrysogaster_-_themaskedlapwing_-_573192220.jpeg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-gerygone", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-gerygone-chrysogaster", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-gerygone", "species": "taxonomy-species-gerygone-chrysogaster"}, "expandable": true, "x": -836.23, "y": 74.98, "z": -145.44}, {"id": "taxonomy-species-gerygone-chrysogaster", "name": "Yellow-bellied gerygone", "latinName": "Gerygone